Cicero was now at the highest point of his success and fame, the recognized head of a moderate party, which aimed to preserve the old institutione of the State, while tempering them with a more liberal policy. But he lacked the qualities of a successful political leader. He was vain, hesitating, lacking sels-control, decision, and dignity of character. As a “new man,’' he never had the full confi· dence of the senatorial farnilies; while his tastes were too much shaped by his Greek training, his mind too delicately organized‚ his ambition too much controlled by sentiment and theory, -we may say, hythe sense of right, -to give him a hold upon the crowd that filled the Forum and carried the Comitia. The leading act of his administration -the suppression of Catiline’s Conspiracy-had‚ by the illegal death ol the conspirators, made him the object of marked hostility to the popular party. The democratic movement became too strong for his feeble grasp, and developed into a destructive radicalism, headed by unscru· Ι pulous gamblers and demagogues‚ which had its natural sequence in civil war and imperialism.
